{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493126"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:57:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:57:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1232"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1232"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.02,0.02,0.93,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1232"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80899"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1232","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1232"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1232"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66225"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"329"},{"type":"tags","id":"2058"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"9222"},{"type":"tags","id":"9450"},{"type":"tags","id":"11637"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"672"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1250"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44508"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44937"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80899","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80899"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of intermittent swelling under his left jaw. The swelling occurs during meals and is associated with dull pain in the same area. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is a visible 3 cm firm swelling in the left submandibular region. Bimanual palpation of the floor of the mouth reveals tenderness. An intraoral X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tonsillitis","Thyroglossal cyst","Branchial cyst","Submandibular duct calculus","Epidermoid cyst"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of sialolithiasis - painful submandibular swelling that worsens with eating. The X-ray confirms the presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Esubmandibular duct calculus\u003C/strong\u003E. The submandibular gland is most commonly affected due to its anatomical features: the duct travels upward against gravity, is relatively long, and contains saliva rich in calcium and mucin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETonsillitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with fever, odynophagia, and visible tonsillar inflammation, none of which are present here. The submandibular location and meal-associated symptoms would be unusual for tonsillitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroglossal cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are midline neck masses that move with tongue protrusion, arising from remnants of the thyroglossal duct. They are typically present from childhood and do not show meal-time variation in symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBranchial cysts\u003C/strong\u003E typically present as painless lateral neck masses anterior to the sternocleidomastoid muscle. They are developmental anomalies that do not typically cause pain or show relationship to eating.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidermoid cysts\u003C/strong\u003E are slow-growing, firm, mobile masses that do not vary with meals. They would not explain the characteristic meal-time symptoms or show calcification on X-ray.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of sialolithiasis is primarily clinical, supported by imaging. Small stones may pass spontaneously, while larger ones may require surgical removal. Complications can include sialadenitis (gland inflammation) and infection if left untreated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Swelling under the jaw associated with meals suggests salivary duct obstruction.","Submandibular glands are most prone to stone formation due to their anatomy and alkaline, calcium-rich secretions.","Diagnosis of sialolithiasis can be confirmed with intraoral X-ray or ultrasound imaging."],"references":["Wilson KF, Meier JD, Ward PD. Salivary gland disorders. Am Fam Physician. 2014;89:882. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25077394/","Alyas F, Lewis K, Williams M, et al. Diseases of the submandibular gland as demonstrated using high resolution ultrasound. Br J Radiol 2005;78:362. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15774602/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66225"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1232"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18428"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18428"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c0ad66d0-7f9d-4a21-9820-00d625f66502.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/c0ad66d0-7f9d-4a21-9820-00d625f66502.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":348,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66225","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66225"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-23T13:47:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-23T13:47:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1232"}},"content":{"